{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "A nationwide fraud ring in the United States around 2020-2021 demonstrated how blending real and fake information could dupe financial institutions.",
    "The perpetrators created synthetic identities by pairing fabricated personal details (names, addresses) with real Social Security numbers stolen from individuals (often children who would not be using their SSNs yet).",
    "With these identities, they opened bank accounts, obtained credit, and even set up shell companies, all under fictitious personas.",
    "Over time, they built credit histories for these \"people\" and then defaulted on loans and credit lines, stealing nearly $2 million from banks before being caught (Department of Homeland Security, 2024).",
    "While this case was primarily a financial crime, it highlighted the ease of creating credible fake personas in the digital record-keeping systems."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Over time, they built credit histories for these \"people\" and then defaulted on loans and credit lines, stealing nearly $2 million from banks before being caught (Department of Homeland Security, 2024)."
  ]
